      • Recent Posts
        • Julie's Bicycle have released the short film of 'Green My Production', their most recent conference on sustainability in theatre, hosted in collaboration with White Light Ltd. Check it out for a great compilation of film cuts from the event, and more than a few industry professionals talking about the potential of green theatre productions, including Bryan Raven of White Light, Sholeh Johnston of Julie's Bicycle and Feimatta Conteh of Arcola Theatre. Also visit Julie's Bicycle's blog for more information on the event, on www.juliesbicycle.com/blog/green-my-production.html !
          Boost Post
        • How is eco-friendly costume and set design also good for your pockets? Take a look at what simple8 theatre company producers Sebastian and Dudley have to say, following their recent productions of 'Moby Dick' and 'The Cabinet of Dr Caligari' using a combined production budget of less than 1000, recycled materials and borrowed set. Thank you Tom Turner for sharing this!
        • We are delighted to hear that the Royal Lyceum Theatre Company are in the forefront of sustainable development in theatre companies! They have recently become the first producing theatre company in the UK to graduate from Carbon Trust Scotland's prestigious Carbon Management Programme. David Tildesley, Buildings Manager at the Lyceum, says: 'How the Lyceum interacts with the environment as a producing theatre is likely to play an increasing role in our future operational funding as a leading Scottish arts organisation. Undertaking the Carbon Management Programme seemed a natural next step if we were serious about how we could as an organisation take collective steps to reduce our environmental impact and become more sustainable.' Congratulations to the Lyceum!
        • Event photos are rolling in. Have a look at our amazing debating team, who explored sustainability as a priority for theatres. Thank you to everyone who participated!
        • Thank you to everyone who joined us and made this wonderful day happen! Special thanks to our debating team, our gorgeous staffers and performers, and all our collaborators and sponsors. Watch this space! We're coming back in 2014.
        • The Improverts workshop today at Bedlam Theatre is running under LED lights.

Malcolm Culleton
7 hrs

As cynical voter with a severe dislike of both major candidates, I wonder who my favorite folk singers would support at this point. Since they're pretty much all dead, I'm just gonna have to guess.

Woody Guthrie would have supported Bernie Sanders but would now be focused on building a third, progressive party while simultaneously playing benefits for an immigrant resistance movement. Pete Seeger would probably be doing it with him. They might both reluctantly bite the bullet... and vote for Hillary if/when the plan fails.

Ritchie Havens would've been a Bernie supporter, but he would've switched to the Hillary camp once Bernie lost the nomination.

John Hurt would've been in the Clinton camp from the start.

Utah Phillips wouldn't be supporting anyone because he was an anarchist who doesn't vote on principle.

Hazel Dickens would've been a Bernie supporter and may or may not have switched over to Hillary by now.

Arlo Guthrie, who is still alive, is probably supporting whoever most passionately supports marijuana legalization.

No one would support Trump, because fascism is completely incompatible with folk music (and art in general).

This exercise isn't helpful.
